Title: Coll. 170. Ms. 593. Page 6
Description.abstract: 1. ff. 1-53v, [Pseudo-Phalaris, Epistolae, translated from the Greek by Francesco Griffolini; ff. 1-4, prologue; red Roman square capitals:] Francisci Aretini in Phalaridis tyranni Agrigentini epistolas ad illustrem principem Malatestam Novellum de Malatestis proemium. [Roman square capitals in black:] Vellem Malatesta Novelle princeps illustris tantam mihi dicendi facultatem dari: ut uel præstantiæ tuæ uel Phalaridis nostri epistolis quas nuper e græco in latinum traductas ... Sed iam Phalarim audiamus. [ff. 4-51v, letters 1-138:] Phalaris Alciboo. Polycletus. Messenius quem proditionis apud cives tuos insimulas ... qui miserit laudem consecuturam. [f. 52, translator's dedication] Franciscus Aretinus divo Alfonso regi. Quatuor Phalaridis epistolas quas nuper in alio libro inventas in latinum traduxi...libens felicissimo nomini tuo dedicabo. [ff. 52-53v, letters 139-142:] Phalaris Ariphanti et Thrabulo. Quas mutuo vobis pecunias dedimus... sed summæ bonitatis premium accepissent. Vale. Τελος. Finis.

Title: Coll. 170. Ms. 593. Page 112
Description.abstract: f. 54r-v, ruled but blank.Pseudo-Phalaris, Epistolae, translated from the Greek by Francesco Griffolini of Arezzo (1418-1483) with dedication to Domenico Novello Malatesta of Cesena (1418-1465); the final four letters are dedicated to King Alfonso I of Naples (1442-1458). 142 epistles falsely attributed to Phalaris, tyrant of Agrigento, s. VI BC; they were actually written by a sophist, s. II AD. Hain *12872-12906; earliest dated printing, Treviso and Paris 1471. The collection of letters in 170/593 closely resembles that in a Venice 1493-95 incunable (minus the edition's concluding dedicatory letter to Francesco Pellato). The list of manuscripts of the Epistolae in D. Muratore, Le Epistole di Falaride; Catalogo dei manoscritti (Rome, 2006) lists MSS containing the Epistolae, does not include 170/593. Marginal pointing hands, bracketing lines, and some underlining of text; contemporary annotations (ff. 19 and 27) in semi-cursive, cut off at the outer edge.
